**(c)** Assume that $p \equiv 3 \pmod{4}$ and $n \equiv x^2 \pmod{p}$. Given $n$ and $p$, find one possible value of $x$. (Hint: Write $p$ as $p = 4k+3$ and use Euler's Criterion. You might have to multiply two sides of an equation by $n$ at one point.)

### Proof
Since $p \equiv 3 \pmod{4}$ then $p = 4k+3$. By Euler's criterion we know:
$$n^{\frac{p-1}{2}} \equiv 1 \pmod{p}$$
**Algebraic manipulation:**
$$\therefore n^{\frac{(4k+3)-1}{2}} \equiv 1 \pmod{p}$$
$$n^{\frac{4k+2}{2}} \equiv 1 \pmod{p}$$
Multiplying both sides by $n$:
$$n \cdot n^{\frac{4k+2}{2}} \equiv n \pmod{p}$$
$$n^{\frac{4k+4}{2}} \equiv n \pmod{p}$$
We know $n \equiv x^2 \pmod{p}$, then:
$$n^{\frac{4k+4}{2}} \equiv x^2 \pmod{p}$$
**Factoring 2:**
$$n^{2\left(\frac{2k+2}{2}\right)} \equiv x^2 \pmod{p}$$
$$n^{2\left(\frac{p+1}{4}\right)} \equiv x^2 \pmod{p}$$
We can see:
$$n^{\left(\frac{p+1}{4}\right)2} \equiv x^2 \pmod{p}$$
$$\therefore x \equiv n^{\frac{p+1}{4}} \pmod{p}$$

