## Problem 4

Prove that for any prime, $p$, and integer, $k \ge 1$, $\phi(p^k) = p^k - p^{k-1}$ where $\phi$ is Euler's function. (Hint: Which numbers between $0$ and $p^k - 1$ are divisible by $p$? How many are there?)

### Proof
Instead of computing the number of integers relatively prime to $p^k$, let's compute factors of $p$ which are:
$$1 \cdot p, 2 \cdot p, \dots, p^{k-1} \cdot p$$
Since $p^{k-1} \cdot p = p^k$ and we also know $p \mid p^k$, we see that $(1, 2, \dots, p^{k-1})$ is a permutation of the number of all multiples of $p$.
Since $p^k - (\text{multiples}) = \phi(p^k)$, then:
$$\phi(p^k) = p^k - p^{k-1}$$
This completes the proof.